        <td bgcolor="dimgray" colspan="2" ><img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="1">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;07/05/2001&nbsp;:&nbsp; 00:52:40</font>

        
		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=784"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=784')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=TopicQuote&TOPIC_ID=5791&FORUM_ID=5&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=The+Necro+Lair&Topic_Title=A+Dance+with+Shadows%3A+Prelude"><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">A Dance with Shadows</P><P>It began in the northern forests, where earth not tread in ages by the feet of evil gently stirred in their wake.  The trees hummed, their leaves wavering in the darkness of a polar wind.  The night was deep, but the shadows deeper, and the moon a pale lantern amidst assailing clouds.  It was a dark night onto a lightless age.  As the moon fell beneath the cloak of clouds, evil grew from the very heart of the earth.  Strangers have set foot upon hallowed lands.</P><P>The Children slept beneath the veils of the forest, cloaked in the mists.  Around them the forest grew, the green of saplings counting years as they waited the gentle spring to bring them vitality and age.  Below the far-reaching trees the younger bushes blossomed with the first flowers of a long awaited rebirth.  The winter has passed and to all that dwelt in the forests a new life had begun.  </P><P>Almost too gentle was the wake from tranquility, yet sudden like from dream.  A sacred trust was broken, whence the first blades touched the flesh of the unspoiled and the untainted.  The trees cried, and their tears turned to blood beneath the falling leaves.  The earth wept, and its tears flowed red into the unspoiled streams.  </P><P>It was almost beautiful, the flames that rose from the northern forests.  It was nearly intricate the way silver flashed amongst those flames, steel upon wood, hate upon dream.  Sudden impulses exploded here and there, voices crying, shouting, and screaming in the darkness.  And then gone, replaced by pristine silence, as if the forest had never been touched at all.  The battles were swift and over quickly, but the scars would last for ages to come.  A dance with shadows, end without beginning.<BR> <BR>When the moon again showed its face to the land, her Children were gone.  The moon searched and searched, but her light no longer could touch the Children’s faces nor fall into their nightly embrace.  For where they slept, no light could touch ever again.</P><P> </P><P>The First King slept beneath the twilight canopies of his timeless palace, he slept and he dreamed.  Dark things came to him in his sleep, tempting him, seducing him, mocking him and threatening him.  They whispered of dark fates and darker destinies.  A pale light shone through their dark faces, and he could see them.  And their faces were his.</P><P>He woke, and beside him woke the First Queen, who watched him rise with eyes that knew their first sorrow and fear.  Starlight fell cascading down her shoulders as she watched him.  Slowly he walked toward the windows and drew them open, dreading.  A cold breeze flew inside like a slithering snake.  Outside, the darkness of the night was hued by a urgent redness that jumped from tree to tree.  An inferno that raged and beat, heated by so many years of jealousy and hate.</P><P>Kneeling beneath the altar of their beloved Goddess, the First King and Queen prayed.  Whether if their prayers were ever heard the tales would not say, for just then the candlelight wavered and from within the flames stood a ghastly figure.  </P><P>He was clad in black, but his face was unseen.  Rising to tower before the King and Queen, he held out to each a hand.  “Embrace my hand, for you know that it alone will save your people from the greed and foolishness of the gods.”</P><P>But the King and Queen shook their heads.</P><P>And the Dark One stood amidst his flames, and a gurgle grew from deep within him.  A gurgling that became a chuckle that became a laugh and then a cackling.  “You would die before you serve me.  But will your daughter die for you? Will she know the torment that only I am capable of? Will you die to doom her, or will you live to save her?”</P><P>The King and the Queen looked at each other, and what shared between them at that moment was a genuine thing, a precious thing, a selfless altruism that the world would not know again for many years.  “And how will we know that she will be safe from you?”</P><P>The flames rose like scourges and whips around the Dark One, and he rasped.  “By the name of the Nameless that even I cannot desecrate, I will not go to your daughter nor taint your people with my own hands, if you shall come with me.”</P><P>And they embraced his hand, and then all three were gone.</P><P></P><P>But the Dark One lied.  The Lord of Lies held to his end of what cannot be broken in the name of the Nameless, but he lied.  For that night, amidst the ruins of the palace where the Children had died for their dreams, a red-hot flame kindled and grew.  In the hearts of those left the flame nourished, drawing on the force of desperation and despair.  The same inferno that marked that cursed night shall mark the world for ages to come.</P><P>And the Dark One lied.  For that night as the Princess Lanys sat lonely upon the throne that lay vacant, in her young and tender heart the same flame grew into an inferno, and it consumed all that was her innocence and kindness.  And though she knew it not yet of it by name, in the depth of her heart Lanys knew that she would come to know hate.</P><P></P><P>And while the gods stood by, the fruits of their inaction even they could not know.  Indeed Innoruuk had sealed the seeds of his final revenge that night.  Indeed two great souls were given to an evil that would corrupt them into a mockery of all that they were.  Indeed a heart and soul was lost that night to hate that could not be redeemed.  But the greatest tragedy of all was that upon that night a dream had died.  A dream of peace, innocence, and kindness smothered beneath the darkness of the world’s greed and the gods’ strife.  And so the dance with shadows began.</P><P> <BR>-------------</P><P>And so begins the EQ epic that I shall be presenting to you as time best allows me.  Don't worry, necros would play a big part in this :) And Faraii, if you're reading this, remember what I said :)</P><P></P><P></P><P>Etadanik the Redeemed</P><P>Edited by - Etadanik Mistmorgue on 07/05/2001  00:54:50</font></td>
